Lo did we come Upon the Ancient Red Wyrm known by the title Abbazur. Mighty was He but Mightier was our Throng as we battled in the name of the Rock of War, to make our Ancestors proud. As that last and Most Ancient Dragon fell we saw to our eternal gratitude the veins of Mithril. Praising Dumathoin's name we added the ore to our gatherings and setting our feet firmly for the Gold depost,
<c>Lo did we come Upon the Ancient Red Wyrm known by the title Abbazur. Mighty was He but Mightier was our Throng as we battled in the name of the Rock of War, to make our Ancestors proud. As that last and Most Ancient Dragon fell we saw to our eternal gratitude the veins of Mithril. Praising Dumathoin's name we added the ore to our gatherings and setting our feet firmly for the Gold depost,
The gnolls fought without a clear battle plan, chaging us in what I deemed 'packs' and attempting to hold our advance. They broke like water upon stone. Along the way we availed outselves of Dumathoin's figts and perfected our formations, since the enemy hardly gave a threat.

[CHAT WINDOW TEXT] [Mon Aug  3 20:54:02] Your patron deity is Dumathoin and you are also worshipping Azuth.
Dumathoin
Dumathoin
Let the record show that twere Skullcleaver of the Blackrock clan, Alaghor and Kuld Baradun Haradunsson Ironshield, Kuld Dwain of Clan Morduum called The Axebringer, Kuld Glognar of Clan Halitt, Runebinder Xartash of Silverymoon and Pathfinder Tulin of Clan Iron Anvil. With chants to Clangeddin upon our beards did we meet the fire giant clan of the isle in battle. Fierce and powerful were our foes, but we proved the fiercer. The giants strove to entrap us, surrounding us, but we locked shields and stood strong, withstood our injuries and fought on. As we pressed toward our goal, the Dumathoin-blessed deposits of Truesilver and precious gems, we met more foes and dispatched them with the fury honed by years of batte.Finally did we venture deeper into the underground, into the lairs of the venerable Red Wyrms themselves. The foul cultists were swept away by our steel, and the dragons numbered Twelve. So it was Twelve we slew that day. Climbing atop their backs and slashing through their skulls or using the power of runes to lay them low, the Wyrmslayer was truly with us as battle chants rose from our lines. 
As that last and Most Ancient Dragon fell we saw to our eternal gratitude the veins of Mithril.Praising Dumathoin's name we added the ore to our gatherings and setting our feet firmly for the Gold deposit, made ready to complete our journey. Twas then we found ourselves again facing a Horde of giants. We bulled our way through their attempt at a front line, cleaving our way to the sorcerous witch among them. Once her head was struck from her body we took the gift of Gold and then, praising each other and Clangeddin for a truly Righteous Battle, did we use the arcane portal and return to our Mighty Mountain. 
The Minmir Caves have long been crowded by all manner of beasts, from gnolls to so-called Banites to a family of great black wyrms. We traveled for a day through the caves, expertly dispatching our foes and following the stalwart Warden. The gnolls fought without a clear battle plan, charging us in what I deemed 'packs' and attempting to hold our advance. They broke like water upon stone. Along the way we availed ourselves of Dumathoin's gifts and perfected our formations, since the enemy hardly gave a threat.

[CHAT WINDOW TEXT] [Thu Sep 10 17:36:54] Your patron deity is Dumathoin and you are also worshipping Azuth.
[CHAT WINDOW TEXT] [Thu Sep 10 19:38:54] Your patron deity is Dumathoin and you are also worshipping Azuth.
Let the record show that twere Skullcleaver of the Blackrock clan, Alaghor and Kuld Baradun Haradunsson Ironshield, Kuld Dwain of Clan Morduum called The Axebringer, Kuld Glognar of Clan Halitt, Runebinder Xartash of Silverymoon and Pathfinder Tulin of Clan Iron Anvil. With chants to Clangeddin upon our beards did we meet the fire giant clan of the isle in battle. Fierce and powerful were our foes, but we proved the fiercer. The giants strove to entrap us, surrounding us, but we locked shields and stood strong, withstood our injuries and fought on. As we pressed toward our goal, the Dumathoin-blessed deposits of Truesilver and precious gems, we met more foes and dispatched them with the fury honed by years of batte.Finally did we venture deeper into the underground, into the lairs of the venerable Red Wyrms themselves. The foul cultists were swept away by our steel, and the dragons numbered Twelve. So it was Twelve we slew that day. Climbing atop their backs and slashing through their skulls or using the power of runes to lay them low, the Wyrmslayer was truly with us as battle chants rose from our lines. 
As that last and Most Ancient Dragon fell we saw to our eternal gratitude the veins of Mithril.Praising Dumathoin's name we added the ore to our gatherings and setting our feet firmly for the Gold deposit, made ready to complete our journey. Twas then we found ourselves again facing a Horde of giants. We bulled our way through their attempt at a front line, cleaving our way to the sorcerous witch among them. Once her head was struck from her body we took the gift of Gold and then, praising each other and Clangeddin for a truly Righteous Battle, did we use the arcane portal and return to our Mighty Mountain. 
The Minmir Caves have long been crowded by all manner of beasts, from gnolls to so-called Banites to a family of great black wyrms. We traveled for a day through the caves, expertly dispatching our foes and following the stalwart Warden. The gnolls fought without a clear battle plan, charging us in what I deemed 'packs' and attempting to hold our advance. They broke like water upon stone. Along the way we availed ourselves of Dumathoin's gifts and perfected our formations, since the enemy hardly gave a threat.

In recognition of The Order of the White Stag's many years of loyal service to the Golden Halls it members are authorized to use all shafts withing the Kinstone Mines.All members of the Order are to be considered Friends of the Halls and have the Thane's blessing to share in Dumathoin's Bounty. For any questions seek me out.
<c>In recognition of The Order of the White Stag's many years of loyal service to the Golden Halls it members are authorized to use all shafts withing the Kinstone Mines.All members of the Order are to be considered Friends of the Halls and have the Thane's blessing to share in Dumathoin's Bounty. For any questions seek me out.

[CHAT WINDOW TEXT] [Thu Feb  4 19:14:06] [Talk] Relds Matulral [Dwarven]: Rurkat, ek ath az th'azla kur th'podrazik dur zihazwak kur dur waurhziath na dur poazthar. Tha rhhazo Dumathoin thazgath k'ath lin.
Let the record show that twere Skullcleaver of the Blackrock clan, Alaghor and Kuld Baradun Haradunsson Ironshield, Kuld Dwain of Clan Morduum called The Axebringer, Kuld Glognar of Clan Halitt, Runebinder Xartash of Silverymoon and Pathfinder Tulin of Clan Iron Anvil. With chants to Clangeddin upon our beards did we meet the fire giant clan of the isle in battle. Fierce and powerful were our foes, but we proved the fiercer. The giants strove to entrap us, surrounding us, but we locked shields and stood strong, withstood our injuries and fought on. As we pressed toward our goal, the Dumathoin-blessed deposits of Truesilver and precious gems, we met more foes and dispatched them with the fury honed by years of batte.Finally did we venture deeper into the underground, into the lairs of the venerable Red Wyrms themselves. The foul cultists were swept away by our steel, and the dragons numbered Twelve. So it was Twelve we slew that day. Climbing atop their backs and slashing through their skulls or using the power of runes to lay them low, the Wyrmslayer was truly with us as battle chants rose from our lines. 
As that last and Most Ancient Dragon fell we saw to our eternal gratitude the veins of Mithril.Praising Dumathoin's name we added the ore to our gatherings and setting our feet firmly for the Gold deposit, made ready to complete our journey. Twas then we found ourselves again facing a Horde of giants. We bulled our way through their attempt at a front line, cleaving our way to the sorcerous witch among them. Once her head was struck from her body we took the gift of Gold and then, praising each other and Clangeddin for a truly Righteous Battle, did we use the arcane portal and return to our Mighty Mountain. 
The Minmir Caves have long been crowded by all manner of beasts, from gnolls to so-called Banites to a family of great black wyrms. We traveled for a day through the caves, expertly dispatching our foes and following the stalwart Warden. The gnolls fought without a clear battle plan, charging us in what I deemed 'packs' and attempting to hold our advance. They broke like water upon stone. Along the way we availed ourselves of Dumathoin's gifts and perfected our formations, since the enemy hardly gave a threat.

Grumbar's foe is usually Akadi, and he has dependable allies in Kurtulmak and Dumathoin. The holy symbol of Grumbar is a sardonyx combined with the symbol of Grumbar (mountains of earth) and is worn by priests of Grumbar.
Grumbar's foe is usually Akadi, and he has dependable allies in Kurtulmak and Dumathoin. The holy symbol of Grumbar is a sardonyx combined with the symbol of Grumbar (mountains of earth) and is worn by priests of Grumbar. 
Given their xenophobic nature it is no surprise that the kobold pantheon have no allies among the gods of other races, however like the duergar god Laduguer, the gnomish god Glittergold and the dwarven god Dumathoin, Kurtulmak shows respect to Grumbar the Earthlord in whose realm his people build their warrens.

Is this true? *frowns a bit* Truly, I do nay know the minds and actions of the gods and goddesses worshipped in Guldorand. I do know Dumathoin and the Morndinsamman and I know that the goodly gods and goddesses would nay do such a thing.
Carry these folks that sacrificed themselves in yer heart.  *taps her chest* Listen to the Morndinsamman, listen to the voice in yer being. What does it tell ye ta do? I am nay wrath, but I am a vessel that the Morndinsamman work through so their wrath can affect the wicked. The exhibitions of Dumathoins wrath are nay arbitrary, for the Morndinsamman take nay pleasure in the punishment o the wicked.

Clan Duergar, which venerated Laduguer as their patron, were an ambitious and powerful clan, believing that they should lead the kingdoms. The rest of the shield dwarves venerated Dumathoin causing more of a rift between the clans. The other clans in the other cities did nay see the Duergar as the rightful and true leaders of the Dwarves and denied them this honor.
Actions, actions, actions, actions *shakes her head* Tis a terrible shame what happened to Clan Duergar. But did our ancestors cause these events? Nay. Did our ancestors allow the mind flayers to descend upon the Duergar clans? Nay. Could we have done something? *looks up* possibly, but Dumathoin will forever keep that secret from me.

The rest of the shield dwarves venerated Dumathoin causing more of a rift between the clans. The other clans in the other cities did nay see the Duergar as the rightful and true leaders of the Dwarves and denied them this honor.
Actions, actions, actions, actions *shakes her head* Tis a terrible shame what happened to Clan Duergar. But did our ancestors cause these events? Nay. Did our ancestors allow the mind flayers to descend upon the Duergar clans? Nay. Could we have done something? *looks up* possibly, but Dumathoin will forever keep that secret from me.
So what is prayer? Dumathoin does not speak to me in a conventional sense. I can not tell you of some grandiose voice from on high that booms into my ears. For that is not Dumathoins way. *smirks* Moradin may do that, I nay know not.
The Blessings I cast every day is a manifestation of this grace left inside me by Dumathoin. I need nay have faith for I manifest his Divine voice, but I do. Faith in what I do, faith in my part in this Hall, faith in my kin.
I prayed how sad I was and how earnest I was to walk the path Dumathoin placed before me. Dumathoin excised my mind and took away my sadness. I was a dwarf of sorrowful spirit no more. I came and poured my spirit before Dumathoin and the abundance of my grief was taken.
Do you think that the Morndinsamman did nay hear your prayer? When Dumathoin does nay answer me, I take council in knowing he answers me when the good of kin are at stake. I may nay be prepared for the mercy of his answer. Or I have to wait a time so I am fit to receive his answer.
Prayer, like Honor, is nay a competition. Prayer is a conversation between you and the Morndinsamman. I converse with Dumathoin every day. *smiles* We are on a first name basis. I talk, He listens. I see His Grace in everything I see; in everyone I meet. 
Either our ancestors are a slab or granite we carry with us, or a feather. It is up to ye to decide. I own the dishonor I caused to my clan and embrace the honor I now have with the Morndinsamman, particularly Dumathoin. Tis a feather for me. It is a burden, one that I pray to be lifted, but still the honor I have been given by the Morndinsamman is a gift.

It is a burden, one that I pray to be lifted, but still the honor I have been given by the Morndinsamman is a gift.
Author's Note: This is the first of many sermons High Talhund Jenvian spoke in the High Temple of Brogendenstein during her stay in the Golden Halls. Her first sermon was centered around Honor as she was exiled and dishonored from the Great Rift and her clan for following Dumathoin. 
I am from the Halls of the Great Rift, a Golden Dwarf as you can plainly see. My name is Jenvian. I am a Talhund o' Dumathoin. I do nay speak my clan name so I do nay give it dishonor. As some of you may know, the Golden Dwarves of the Rift lay out each child's path when they are born. What skill they will practice, who they marry and how they will bring honor to their clan. 
*speaks with a louder voice* So I called out to the Morndinsamman to allow me to live longer so I may bring honor to my clan. Out of the entire Morndinsamman, Dumathoin answered me. He offered me a terrible honor. 
Dumathoin would breath his most divine breath upon me, healing me and allowing me to survive this near death experience. The terrible honor I would pay would be to serve Him for the rest of my life. Some terrible honor.. a Talhund
But for me, to serve Dumathoin would mean I would nay longer stay in the Great Rift. I would reject the betrothyl and take to the paths known only to the Morndinsamman. So this honor I now walked caused my clan, my ancestors, and my family dishonor as I did not complete the path I have walked over the last century. 
But I also know that I, and perhaps some of you, will never be the beneficiary of honor grown from the clan. I have chosen to forgo that rich spiritual heritage that has been passed down through family from generation to generation. I am the very first Talhund in my clan. I have listened to stories of my clan and there has been Solinnars but nay acolytes o' Dumathoin. 
And if thats the case, then Dumathoin, in His infinite wisdom and grace, has provided me the Morndinsamman as my spiritual parents that have dug the first mines in my life.
Dumathoin commands me to honor the ancestors. So I go down to the crypts below the hold here and make sure the dead are taken care of. Dumathoin did nay tell me to kill every walkin' dead, creature and worm down there, I just did that on my own. *smiles* Its a perk.
*beats her fist on her chest over her heart* It is MY honor that I do this. I embrace the choice Dumathoin gives me and my action speaks to those that can listen. *points a finger at all of them and gets a bit animated* That is YOUR honor! Choose what is right for you. Choose your path and declare to the realms your decision. Right or wrong, it shall be honorable! 
Right or wrong, it shall be honorable! Do ye think my father thought I made the 'right' decision to follow the path Dumathoin set before me? Abandoning the path my father set for me as an infant? Honor is nay about right and wrong, but to stay true to oneself, to listen to the Morndinsamman in yer heart and do what 'you' think is right.

Honor is nay about right and wrong, but to stay true to oneself, to listen to the Morndinsamman in yer heart and do what 'you' think is right. 
For the Morndinsamman will be with us during battle. I know that Dumathoin will be with me during conflict. I am certain that Moradin, Clangeddin, Gorm and the rest of our Morndinsamman will be with us during our times of need. 
But Dumathoin has nay mentioned to me we are going ta war. Not yet anyhow. When he does, if he does, we should also know we should give peace a chance as well. For the call ta war is the last resort we have and the stopping o' war should be the only thing on our mind when we are at war.

I am from the Halls of the Great Rift, a Golden Dwarf as you can plainly see. My name is Jenvian. I am a Talhund o' Dumathoin. I do nay speak my clan name so I do nay give it dishonor. As some of you may know, the Golden Dwarves of the Rift lay out each child's path when they are born. What skill they will practice, who they marry and how they will bring honor to their clan. 
*speaks with a louder voice* So I called out to the Morndinsamman to allow me to live longer so I may bring honor to my clan. Out of the entire Morndinsamman, Dumathoin answered me. He offered me a terrible honor. 
Dumathoin would breath his most divine breath upon me, healing me and allowing me to survive this near death experience. The terrible honor I would pay would be to serve Him for the rest of my life. Some terrible honor.. a Talhund
But for me, to serve Dumathoin would mean I would nay longer stay in the Great Rift. I would reject the betrothyl and take to the paths known only to the Morndinsamman. So this honor I now walked caused my clan, my ancestors, and my family dishonor as I did not complete the path I have walked over the last century. 
But I also know that I, and perhaps some of you, will never be the beneficiary of honor grown from the clan. I have chosen to forgo that rich spiritual heritage that has been passed down through family from generation to generation. I am the very first Talhund in my clan. I have listened to stories of my clan and there has been Solinnars but nay acolytes o' Dumathoin. 
And if thats the case, then Dumathoin, in His infinite wisdom and grace, has provided me the Morndinsamman as my spiritual parents that have dug the first mines in my life.
Dumathoin commands me to honor the ancestors. So I go down to the crypts below the hold here and make sure the dead are taken care of. Dumathoin did nay tell me to kill every walkin' dead, creature and worm down there, I just did that on my own. *smiles* Its a perk.
*beats her fist on her chest over her heart* It is MY honor that I do this. I embrace the choice Dumathoin gives me and my action speaks to those that can listen. *points a finger at all of them and gets a bit animated* That is YOUR honor! Choose what is right for you. Choose your path and declare to the realms your decision. Right or wrong, it shall be honorable! 
Right or wrong, it shall be honorable! Do ye think my father thought I made the 'right' decision to follow the path Dumathoin set before me? Abandoning the path my father set for me as an infant? Honor is nay about right and wrong, but to stay true to oneself, to listen to the Morndinsamman in yer heart and do what 'you' think is right. 
For the Morndinsamman will be with us during battle. I know that Dumathoin will be with me during conflict. I am certain that Moradin, Clangeddin, Gorm and the rest of our Morndinsamman will be with us during our times of need. 
But Dumathoin has nay mentioned to me we are going ta war. Not yet anyhow. When he does, if he does, we should also know we should give peace a chance as well. For the call ta war is the last resort we have and the stopping o' war should be the only thing on our mind when we are at war.
